Module 19 – Procedural History Is Your Weaponized Timeline 🗓️📜

Core Message

Procedural history isn’t filler — it’s your curated story of the case.

⸻

Lesson Introduction

A well-crafted procedural history can highlight patterns, expose bad faith, and frame the court’s reading of the facts.

⸻

Teaching Block

1. Select Key Events
	•	Include only entries that matter to your argument.

2. Show Patterns
	•	Cluster similar actions to reveal suppression or delay tactics.

3. Integrate Into Argument
	•	Tie each procedural event to the harm or relief sought.

⸻

Real-World Illustration

In federal filings, a procedural history table was used to show repeated delays in docketing TRO filings.

⸻

Assignment Prompt

Task:
Make a 5-entry procedural history for a hypothetical TRO motion.

⸻

Model Answer (Sample)
	1.	7/1 – Motion filed.
	2.	7/3 – Opposition filed.
	3.	7/7 – Supplemental brief filed.
	4.	7/14 – No ruling.
	5.	7/21 – Motion refiled.

⸻

Reflection Summary

Procedural history is an advocacy tool — not just a record.

⸻

Visual Pairing

Image Concept:
A timeline with red flags marking each procedural irregularity. Caption:
“History That Speaks for You.”
